(c)

Energy of valleyvalley is about 0.30.3 eVeV lower than LvalleyLvalley. So, when voltage drop across icollectoricollector exceeds 0.30.3 VV, LvalleyLvalley in sub-collector becomes lower than valleyvalley in subcolectorsubcolector. Also, electric field and energy is high enough to promote transfer of electrons to LvalleyLvalley. So, this leads to intervalley transfer of some electrons from valleyvalley in basebase to LvalleyLvalley in subcollectorsubcollector. Since effective mass is higher in LvalleyLvalley compared to valleyvalley, mobility is lower in LvalleyLvalley compared to valleyvalley. So, electron velocity is lower in LvalleyLvalley compared to valleyvalley.

So, when collector voltage drop is greater than 0.30.3 VV, electron velocity is lower compared to electron velocity when collector voltage drop is less than 0.30.3 VV.

So, to maintain collector voltage drop below 0.30.3 VV, a p-type dopant sheet is put at icollectoricollector and subcollectorsubcollector interface. Dopant sheet accepts electrons from neighbouring subcollectorsubcollector and becomes a negatively charge sheet. This negatively charge sheet screens the electric field due to the depletion charge in subcollectorsubcollector. So, electric field in icollectoricollector is lower in comparision to the electric field in absense of p-type dopant sheet. This means lower collector voltage drop in comparision to the collector voltage drop in absense of p-type dopant sheet. By increasing the dopant sheet charge (by increasing its thickness and doping), collector voltage drop can made less than 0.30.3 VV.

At short times, electrons remain in valleyvalley with light effective mass and achieve high velocities. However, once they achieve energies comparable to LvalleyLvalley (0.30.3 eVeV), transfer to LvalleyLvalley with higher effective mass takes place accompanied by loss in velocity. At higher times, the high effective mass in LvalleyLvalley prevents transferred electrons from acheiving higher velocities. Also, there are scatterings in and out of the LvalleyLvalley. Due to this intevalley transfer, velocity overshoot occurs in Gallium Arsenide. So, ballistic collector transistors use this p-type dopant sheet to prevent velocity overshoot (due to intervalley transfer) and hence electrons move at velocity greater than saturation velocity. Due to lower scattering, the transport is near ballistic and this is unique to ballisctic collector transsistor. Due to higher electron velocity compared to conventional BJT (absense of p-type dopant sheet) , transit delay is less in comparision to conventional BJT.
